\s2 This is a demonstration of some of the new picture positions.
\p
\v 1 There are three new picture positions, for when the normal
top-left/bottom-right, etc. are not sufficient. These positions are: 
\q1 '\bd here\bd*', also known as  'in-line';  
\q1 '\bd cut-out\bd*' or 'wrapped'  which makes a notch in the
text; 
\q1 '\bd post-paragraph\bd*' or 'delayed', mainly
for the end of chapters, when there is no verse to put the picture before.  
\m Each of the positions
have left and right variations, the 'here' and 'delayed' have a centred option
too.  
\v 2 There is no paragraph break in the text here, before the verse that the pic will attach to. An in-line or cut-out image must 
have a paragraph break so it will force one (same type as last-time).  
\p
\v 3 A new paragraph mid cut-out does not  cause  a problem.  And a cut-out will stop 
without a new paragraph starting. 
\p Notice that the image did not
start at the start of the paragraph, but some lines lower. That is determined by
the digit that follows the side. 
\p Left and right variations have captions the same width as the picture, centred ones get the whole column/page width.
\p Don't rely on forced paragraphs, particularly if you intend to insert another image. Two cut-outs in a 
single paragraph cause problems.
